'''Alisa Melekhina''' (born June 26, 1991) is one of the top female chess players in the United States,{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} a classically trained [[ballerina]], and an alumna of the [[University of Pennsylvania Law School]].

Melekhina is a frequent contender in the [[U.S. Women's Chess Championship]],<ref>[http://gambit.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/09/zatonskih-the-defending-champion-leads-us-womens-championship/#more-1527]</ref><ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|last=Barbara |first=By |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703298004574457393421190888 |title=Abolish Women's Chess Titles - WSJ |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=2009-10-14 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> and has represented the [[United States]] in numerous World Youth and Junior Chess Championships, where she has placed in the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chess: Dmitry Andreikin wins world junior title|url=http://www.latimes.com/features/puzzles/chess/la-ca-0822-chess-20100822,0,936955.story|website=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> She placed fifth at the 2014 US Women's Championships.<ref>http://uschesschamps.com/node/429</ref> She graduated from the University of Pennsylvania Law School aged 22, in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uschesschamps.com/bio/alisa-melekhina |title=Alisa Melekhina |publisher=www.uschesschamps.com |date=2012-03-23 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Melekhina was born in [[Simferopol]] in 1991.<ref name="philly1">{{cite web|author=Dan Gross |url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-04-18/entertainment/31361832_1_chess-alisa-melekhina-fashion-line |title=Local chess prodigy goes for women's championship - Philly.com |publisher=Articles.philly.com |date=2013-02-26 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> She immigrated with her parents to the United States when she was only two months old. They originally settled in [[Brooklyn, New York]] while her father completed his dental re-accreditation. They moved to [[Philadelphia]] five years later, where Melekhina has resided since. Melekhina was taught to play chess by her father and only coach at age 5, and played in her first tournament when she was 7. She also began taking [[Vaganova]]-style ballet lessons at that age, and has been dancing ballet and pointe since.<ref name="uschess1">{{cite web|url=http://www.uschess.org/content/view/12585/757/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - Legal Moves: Melekhina on Chess & Law School |publisher=Uschess.org |date=2014-03-16 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> At age 6, she authored “[[The Frog Princess]],” a translation of a popular Russian fairy tale, making her a published author at age 8.<ref name="philly1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Frog-Princess-Russian-Melekhina-ebook/dp/B00CZCT3MW |title=The Frog Princess: A Russian Fairy Tale, Retold by Alisa Melekhina eBook: Alisa Melekhina: Kindle Store |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>

== Chess achievements ==

Melekhina's top chess accomplishments include:
*Finishing top 10 at the World Youths and World Junior Chess Championships.
*Winning the gold medal best individual board four performance at the Women's World Championships held in Ningbo, China in 2009 Team<ref name="nytimes1">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/20/nyregion/20chess.html]</ref>
*Securing an IM Norm at the Chicago North American Invitational RR series in 2009<ref name="uschess1"/>
*Placing third at the prestigious U.S. Women's Championships in 2009 at age 18, held in St. Louis<ref name="autogenerated1"/>
*Tying for third in the competitive, high-stakes World Open U2400 section in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uschess.org/content/view/10524/596/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - The Scoop on the World Open |publisher=Uschess.org |date=2010-07-06 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
*First Female Pennsylvania State Champion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://main.uschess.org/content/view/10752/141/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - Bartell and Melekhina Share PA State Title |publisher=Main.uschess.org |date=2010-10-19 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
*She earned the FIDE Master title in 2011 and prefers to go by this over her Women's International Master title<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=2022613 |title=Melekhina, Alisa FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers |publisher=Ratings.fide.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>

== Notable games ==

*Melekhina won one of the best game prizes for her win over [[Woman Grandmaster|WGM]] [[Tatev Abrahamyan]] at the 2009 U.S. Women's Chess Championships as black against the Italian Opening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uschess.org/content/view/9808/556/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - 9Queens Presents the Best Games at the U.S. Women's |publisher=Uschess.org |date=2009-10-28 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
*Her win over one of China's top female players as black in the Trompowsky Opening was featured in the print-version of the New York Times.<ref name="nytimes1"/>
*One her most notable games is a c3 Sicilian miniature over [[Grandmaster (chess)|GM]] [[Alexander Shabalov]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uschess.org/content/view/11276/632/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - Philadelphia International Underway |publisher=Uschess.org |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
*In December of that year she beat GM and US Women's Champion [[Irina Krush]] on the black side of the rare Bg4 line of the [[King's Indian Defense]]<ref name="uschess1"/>
*Melekhina's favorite tournament game is a win in the same c3 Sicilian line where she sacrificed a bishop and rook to get a fatal mating attack, forcing her opponent to give up his queen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uschess.org/content/view/12634/760/ |title=The United States Chess Federation - Kamsky Tops Philly on Way to Saint Louis |publisher=Uschess.org |date=2014-04-22 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
*Melekhina played the [[Blumenfeld Gambit]] against [[Irina Krush]] in round 6 of the 2014 US Women's Championships, leading to an exciting draw with several exchange sacrifices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chess.com/news/akobian-leads-us-championship-after-round-7-5723 |title=Akobian Leads U.S. Championship After Round 7 |publisher=Chess.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>

== Chess videos and publications ==

Melekhina was an inspiration for ''The Fire'' Katherine Neville's sequel to the chess-themed historical fiction ''The Eight''.

Melekhina is a content creator for onlinechesslessons.net<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlinechesslessons.net/?s=Melekhina&lang=en |title=Phrase: Melekhina &#124; Chess Videos, Chess DVDs, Chess Software and more |publisher=Onlinechesslessons.net |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> and chess.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chess.com/video/library?author=Alisa_Melekhina |title=Chess Videos, Lessons, & Chess Lectures |publisher=Chess.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> Her instructional videos include topics on the c3 Sicilian, Advanced French, King's Indian Defense, Fighting in the Endgame, Power of the Double Rooks, and Defeating Drawish Players. Her famous video on “How to Win in the c3 Sicilian in 21 Moves or Less,” featuring her win over GM Shabalov has received over 160,000 hits on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1vaTT8jcDf4 |title=How to Win in the c3 Sicilian in 21 moves or less - FM Alisa Melekhina |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-06-18 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref>
Before beginning law school, she co-authored a journal article on whether chess games can be copyrighted.<ref>[http://jiplp.oxfordjournals.org/content/6/10/723.abstract]</ref>

Melekhina was featured on the cover of the April 2015 edition of [[Chess Life]] magazine, authoring an article on "Career Crossroads."<ref>http://www.uschess.org/content/view/13009/365</ref>

== Professional career ==
Melekhina graduated from [[Drexel University]] with a bachelor's degree in [[Philosophy]] in only two years at age 19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.drexel.edu/alumni/spotlight_melekhina.asp |title=Drexel University Alumni |publisher=Drexel.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140618044609/http://drexel.edu/alumni/spotlight_melekhina.asp |archive-date=2014-06-18 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> She began University of Pennsylvania Law School in 2011, and was the youngest in her class at age 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbar.org/publications/student_lawyer/2012-13/sept/head_of_the_class.html |title=A Master in the Making &#124; Law Student Division |publisher=Americanbar.org |date= |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> While at law school she founded an Eastern European Law Students Association (EELSA) affinity group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/news/penn-s-strong-global-community-attracts-growing-number-international-students |title=Penn News &#124; Penn’s Strong Global Community Attracts Growing Number of International Students |publisher=Upenn.edu |date=2013-12-16 |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> After graduating law school, Melekhina is now a litigation associate practicing in [[white-collar crime|white-collar]] and [[intellectual property]] litigation at Debevoise & Plimpton LLP in New York City.<ref>http://www.debevoise.com/alisamelekhina/?tab=Biography</ref> She previously founded SubLite: a portal for student summer sublets and internships.<ref>[http://sublite.net/#about]</ref>

